Following the conclusion of the pilot study, the core methodological pipeline was
transferred without modification to the expanded cohort. The same One-vs-Rest (OvR)
XGBoost architecture described in Section~\ref{sec:xgboost_final} — fitted by binary
cross-entropy, evaluated with macro-averaged F1-score, and regularised identically to
the pilot configuration — was applied to the 702-sample expanded cohort. No
hyperparameter re-tuning was performed: the objective of this chapter is not to find
the best possible model for the larger dataset, but to assess whether the patterns
identified in the pilot cohort \textbf{generalise} to a broader and independently
assembled patient sample. Holding the model architecture fixed is therefore an explicit
methodological choice that preserves comparability.

Both feature configurations were evaluated in parallel:
\textbf{miRNA only} (539 features) and \textbf{miRNA + clinical} (539 miRNA + 15
clinical features = 554 features). The expanded cohort was split using the same
stratified 80/20 protocol described in Section~\ref{sec:expanded_preprocessing},
yielding 561 training and 141 test samples with subtype proportions preserved across
both partitions. Tables~\ref{tab:homogenous_comparison}
and~\ref{tab:heterogeneous_comparison} report the full set of performance metrics for
both conditions alongside the corresponding pilot-cohort values, with differences
colour-coded to highlight regressions (red) and improvements (green).


