\subsection{Per-Subtype Classification Performance}
\label{sec:expanded_per_subtype}

The aggregate picture in Tables~\ref{tab:homogenous_comparison}
and~\ref{tab:heterogeneous_comparison} conceals important per-subtype variation.
The following paragraphs interpret the detailed binary classification reports produced
for each OvR classifier, following the same structure used in
Section~\ref{sec:model-results} so that the two analyses can be read in parallel.

% ==========================================
\subsubsection{Basal-Like}
% ==========================================

The Basal-like subtype continues to be the most reliably identified class in the
expanded cohort. In the miRNA-only configuration, the OvR classifier achieves a
precision of 1.00, recall of 0.96, and F1-score of 0.98 for the Basal-like class,
representing only a marginal decrease from the perfect scores obtained in the pilot
cohort. With the addition of clinical features, the classifier recovers to a perfect
F1-score of 1.00, reaching precision 1.00 and recall 1.00 across all test samples.
This remarkable performance, maintained at scale on a nearly three-fold larger
dataset, confirms the \textbf{strong and distinct miRNA expression signature}
characteristic of Basal-like tumours observed in the pilot study. As detailed in
Section~\ref{sec:booster-features}, the XGBoost booster identifies MIR-577 as the
dominant discriminative feature for this subtype across both conditions — a finding
that directly replicates the pilot study's conclusions.

[MEDIA] Table: binary classification report for Basal-like, both conditions
(test set $n = 141$: 24 Basal-like, 117 Not Basal-like).

% ==========================================
\subsubsection{HER2-Enriched}
% ==========================================

HER2-enriched remains the most difficult subtype to classify, consistent with the
pilot study. In the miRNA-only condition, the classifier achieves an F1-score of
0.42 for the HER2-enriched class (precision 0.67, recall 0.31), indicating that
while false positives are limited, the model misses a substantial fraction of true
HER2-enriched cases. The weighted-average F1-score across both classes is 0.91,
reflecting the strong performance on the much larger \textit{Not HER2-enriched}
group.

The addition of clinical covariates yields a meaningful improvement: the
HER2-enriched F1-score rises to 0.57 (precision 0.75, recall 0.46), a gain of
$+0.15$ in F1 for the positive class. This is particularly notable given that the
expanded cohort \textbf{does not include HER2 receptor status} as a clinical feature
— in the pilot study, \texttt{HER2\_STATUS} was the single most powerful clinical
predictor for this subtype (Section~\ref{sec:anova-bridge}). The improvement seen
here is instead driven by genomic instability metrics, with the Buffa Hypoxia Score
emerging as the second most important feature for HER2-enriched classification in the
combined condition (Section~\ref{sec:expanded_booster}). Despite the improvement,
HER2-enriched remains the clearest bottleneck in the pipeline, and the consistent
difficulty across both cohorts suggests it is a property of the subtype's
transcriptomic landscape rather than a dataset-size artefact.

[MEDIA] Table: binary classification report for HER2-enriched, both conditions
(test set: 13 HER2-enriched, 128 Not HER2-enriched).

% ==========================================
\subsubsection{Luminal A}
% ==========================================

Luminal A classification yields solid performance on the expanded cohort. The
miRNA-only classifier achieves F1-scores of 0.87 (\textit{Not Luminal A}) and 0.90
(\textit{Luminal A}), for a macro-averaged F1 of 0.89. The miRNA + clinical
configuration produces a slightly lower macro-average of 0.88 — the two conditions
are essentially equivalent, suggesting that the available clinical features (hypoxia
and genomic instability scores) add little discriminative signal for a subtype whose
identity is primarily encoded in the miRNA expression profile.

Luminal A's comparatively high separability, despite its class dominance in the
dataset (51.6\% of samples), is consistent with the pilot study's findings and with
its biological distinctiveness as the low-proliferation, hormone receptor-positive
subtype. The OvR framing benefits from the large number of positive training
examples, but the high recall (0.96 in miRNA-only) indicates that the model is
genuinely learning the Luminal A miRNA signature rather than simply predicting the
majority class.

[MEDIA] Table: binary classification report for Luminal A, both conditions
(test set: 73 Luminal A, 68 Not Luminal A).

% ==========================================
\subsubsection{Luminal B}
% ==========================================

Luminal B is the second most challenging subtype, replicating the pattern observed
in the pilot study. In the miRNA-only condition, the F1-score for the Luminal B class
is 0.56 (precision 0.74, recall 0.45), reflecting the subtype's known transcriptomic
heterogeneity and its partial overlap with Luminal A in miRNA space. The
addition of clinical features improves the Luminal B F1-score to 0.65 (precision
0.75, recall 0.58), a gain of $+0.09$ in F1 for the positive class. As with
HER2-enriched, the improvement arises without access to receptor status annotations;
instead, the Ragnum Hypoxia Score and MSI-related features provide a modest but
consistent supplementary signal (Section~\ref{sec:expanded_booster}).

The persistent difficulty with Luminal B — a subtype that shares many miRNA
expression characteristics with Luminal A and differs primarily in its higher
proliferative index — is consistent across both cohorts and reinforces one of the
central conclusions of this work: the miRNA-driven separability gradient
\textbf{Basal-like > Luminal A > HER2-enriched $\approx$ Luminal B} is a robust
property of the TCGA-BRCA data that scales with cohort size.

[MEDIA] Table: binary classification report for Luminal B, both conditions
(test set: 31 Luminal B, 110 Not Luminal B).


