\section{Feature Extraction and Statistical Corroboration}
\label{sec:expanded_features}

The supervised classification results in the previous section establish that the
XGBoost pipeline generalises well to the expanded cohort, at least for subtypes with
strong transcriptomic signatures. However, strong classification performance is only a
means to an end: the model is used here as a \textbf{proxy} whose internal structure
can be interrogated to retrieve the miRNAs and clinical variables that carry the most
subtype-specific discriminative information. Accordingly, this section applies the
same two-level feature extraction and validation strategy developed in
Section~\ref{sec:booster-features} and Section~\ref{sec:anova-bridge}: per-subtype
gain importances from the XGBoost booster, followed by an independent ANOVA F-test
to assess whether the highest-ranked features are also \textbf{individually} and
\textbf{statistically} separable across subtypes.

As in the pilot study, both methods are treated as complementary rather than
redundant. XGBoost gain captures the incremental predictive value of a feature
\textit{within the model's multivariate decision process}; ANOVA F-test captures the
marginal statistical separation of a feature across subtype groups \textit{in
isolation}. A feature that is selected by both methods independently constitutes a
stronger biomarker candidate than one flagged by either method alone.

% ----------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{XGBoost Feature Importances}
\label{sec:expanded_booster}
% ----------------------------------------------------------

Following the procedure described in Section~\ref{sec:booster-features}, the
internal XGBoost booster was used to extract per-subtype gain importances for each
OvR binary classifier. The top 20 features by total gain are reported below for each
subtype and each feature configuration.

\subsubsection{Basal-Like Feature Panel}

The Basal-like gain importance landscape in the expanded cohort is dominated by
\textbf{MIR-577} to an even greater degree than in the pilot study. In the
miRNA-only configuration, MIR-577 accounts for 46.58\% of the total gain, already
a substantial majority; with clinical features added, its share rises further to
64.15\%. This dominance — consistent across both cohorts and both feature
configurations — makes MIR-577 the \textbf{most robustly supported candidate
discriminative miRNA} for the Basal-like subtype in this work.

Beyond MIR-577, the core panel is stable: MIR-934 (6.45\%), MIR-18a (5.68\%),
MIR-2115 (4.76\%), MIR-4446 (4.71\%), MIR-135b (4.00\%), MIR-671 (3.27\%), and
MIR-190b (3.11\%) complete the top eight in the miRNA-only condition, and are all
replicated in the miRNA + clinical ranking. The collective gain of the top-20
features reaches 92.0\% in the miRNA-only condition and 94.0\% with clinical data,
indicating an unusually concentrated importance structure consistent with a
subtype-specific miRNA programme rather than diffuse expression differences.

[MEDIA] Bar chart: Top 20 XGBoost gain importances for Basal-like,
miRNA-only vs. miRNA + clinical (side-by-side or overlaid).

\subsubsection{HER2-Enriched Feature Panel}

The HER2-enriched importance landscape is considerably more distributed, with no
single feature dominating. In the miRNA-only configuration, the leading feature
MIR-4728 captures only 8.17\% of total gain, and the top-20 features together
account for 57.1\%. With clinical features, the importance becomes slightly more
concentrated (top-20 gain: 64.7\%), with the Buffa Hypoxia Score entering at second
place (6.62\%), following MIR-4791 (8.38\%). The emergence of a transcriptomic
hypoxia signature as a discriminative clinical feature for HER2-enriched tumours is
biologically plausible, given the known association between HER2 amplification,
angiogenic dysregulation, and tumour hypoxia. Other consistent top-ranking miRNAs
across both configurations include MIR-2115, MIR-6733, MIR-2355, and MIR-4728.

The distributed importance structure for HER2-enriched directly mirrors the subtype's
classification difficulty: a subtype that cannot be cleanly separated from a small
set of dominant features will naturally produce a classifier with limited recall, as
observed in Section~\ref{sec:expanded_per_subtype}.

[MEDIA] Bar chart: Top 20 XGBoost gain importances for HER2-enriched,
miRNA-only vs. miRNA + clinical.

\subsubsection{Luminal A Feature Panel}

For Luminal A, the miRNA-only condition assigns the highest gain to \textbf{MIR-590}
(8.84\%), followed by MIR-130b (4.97\%), with the remaining top-20 features each
contributing less than 3\%. The collective gain of the top-20 is 42.9\%, indicating
a moderate degree of concentration. In the miRNA + clinical condition, the
\textbf{Ragnum Hypoxia Score} displaces MIR-590 as the leading feature (6.17\% gain),
with MIR-590 falling to second place (5.50\%). The entry of a hypoxia score as the
most informative feature in the multivariate context is a notable departure from the
pilot study, in which the receptor status features dominated the Luminal A clinical
panel. This shift reflects the different clinical annotation available in the expanded
cohort and illustrates how the identity of informative clinical features is
\textit{annotation-dependent} rather than intrinsic to the subtype biology.

The relatively diffuse importance structure for Luminal A (top-20 gain $<45\%$ in
both conditions) is consistent with this subtype's large class size and its overlap
with Luminal B: the model must leverage many features to partition the majority class.

[MEDIA] Bar chart: Top 20 XGBoost gain importances for Luminal A,
miRNA-only vs. miRNA + clinical.

\subsubsection{Luminal B Feature Panel}

The Luminal B importance landscape shows one notable shift relative to the pilot
study. In the miRNA + clinical condition, \textbf{MIR-190b} emerges as the dominant
feature (8.90\% gain), a position it did not occupy in the pilot cohort. MIR-193b
(4.20\%) and MIR-301a (3.04\%) follow in both configurations, providing some
stability. The entry of MIR-190b as a leading feature is worth noting: this miRNA
was also identified as important for both Basal-like and Luminal B in the pilot study,
suggesting it may capture a cross-subtype signal related to tumour aggressiveness or
cell proliferation rather than strict subtype specificity.

As in the pilot study, the collective gain of the Luminal B top-20 features
($\approx 43$\% in miRNA-only; $\approx 46$\% with clinical) remains the lowest
among all subtypes, confirming the broader observation that Luminal B is the
\textbf{least concentrated} in the miRNA feature importance space — a direct
consequence of its transcriptomic heterogeneity.

[MEDIA] Bar chart: Top 20 XGBoost gain importances for Luminal B,
miRNA-only vs. miRNA + clinical.

