The ANOVA results replicate and strengthen several findings from the pilot study.
First, the \textbf{separability gradient across subtypes} is preserved: Basal-like
achieves the highest best F1-score (0.947 / 0.944) regardless of condition, followed
by Luminal A (0.857 / 0.883), HER2-enriched (0.676 / 0.718), and Luminal B
(0.555 / 0.684). This ranking is consistent with both the XGBoost OvR results and
the pilot-study ANOVA sweep, suggesting it reflects a genuine property of the
data's underlying geometry rather than a model-specific or cohort-specific artefact.

Second, the \textbf{optimal feature count} for Basal-like (95–100 features) is
substantially higher than for HER2-enriched (20–65) and Luminal B (25–30), despite
Basal-like being the most separable subtype. This counterintuitive observation
replicates the pilot study and can be understood as follows: Basal-like has a very
strong signal that is distributed across many correlated miRNAs (as evidenced by the
broad F-score distribution), whereas for HER2-enriched and Luminal B the
incremental contribution of additional features is limited, and the performance
plateaus — or slightly degresses — beyond a small number of top-ranked features.

Third, the addition of clinical features generally \textbf{improves} the ANOVA
best F1-score for HER2-enriched ($+0.042$), Luminal A ($+0.026$) and Luminal B
($+0.129$), while leaving Basal-like virtually unchanged ($-0.003$). The large
gain for Luminal B is particularly striking: with only 30 features, the combined
model achieves an F1-score of 0.684 compared to 0.555 with miRNA alone. This
suggests that at least some of the expanded cohort's genomic instability and
hypoxia clinical features carry signals that are partially orthogonal to the miRNA
expression space for this subtype.

